# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bosnian-cyrillic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/a-with-ring-above-cyrillic] A with ring above is used only in the alphabet of the Selkup language, where it represents the open-mid back rounded vowel /ɔ/ or the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] Its name in Serbo-Croatian is *Bosančica* and *Bosanica* the latter of which might be translated as *Bosnian script*.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] Some of those who wrote in that script referred to it as the Serbian Script.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] Neutral scholars call it *Western Cyrillic*.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] Serb scholars call it *Serbian Script*, *Serbian Letters*, *Serbian–Bosnian script*, *Bosnian–Serb Cyrillic*, *Serbian Western Cyrillic*, *Serbian Minuscule*, as part of variant of Serbian Cyrillic and deem the term "bosančica" Anti-Serbian Austro-Hungarian propaganda.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] Croat scholars also call it *Croatian script*, *Croatian–Bosnian script*, *Bosnian–Croat Cyrillic*, *harvacko pismo*, *arvatica*.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] For other names of Bosnian Cyrillic, see below.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] The use of Bosančica amongst Bosnian Muslims was replaced by Arebica upon the introduction of Islam in Bosnia Eyalet, first amongst the elite, then amongst the wider public.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] The first book in Bosančica was printed by Frančesko Micalović in 1512 in Venice.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] It is hard to ascertain when the earliest features of a characteristic Bosnian type of Cyrillic script had begun to appear, but some paleographers consider the Humac tablet to be the first document of this type of script and is believed to date between 10th to 12th century.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] Bosnian Cyrillic was used continuously until the 18th century, with sporadic usage even taking place in the 20th century.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] Controversy about "ethnic affiliation" of Bosnian Cyrillic started in the 19th century, reappearing in the mid-1990s.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] In 2015, a group of artists started a project called "I write to you in Bosančica" which involved art and graphic design students from Banja Luka, Sarajevo, Široki Brijeg, and Trebinje.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] Exhibitions of the submitted artworks will be held in Sarajevo, Trebinje, Široki Brijeg, Zagreb, and Belgrade.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] The purpose of the project was to resurrect the ancient script and show the "common cultural past" of all the groups in Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] The first phase of the project was to reconstruct all of the ancient characters by using ancient, handwritten documents.
[src:bosnian-cyrillic/bosnian-cyrillic] The name *bosančica* was first used by Fran Kurelac in 1861.
